Tariro Sajeni  STAFF WRITER sajenit@dailynews.co.zw 245 THE Coca-Cola Foundation has donated US$50 000 to DanChurchAid Zimbabwe to help implement a much-needed water and sanitation project for Bulawayo during this Covid-19 pandemic. At least 25 000 people are expected to benefit from the project that aims to provide clean and safe water by financing site surveys and the drilling of boreholes. Bulawayo is currently going through one of its worst water crises in years with some suburbs going for six months without the precious liquid. Other locations in the second city have to go through a very punishing water rationing schedule, forcing residents to resort to unprotected and unsafe water sources. The Bulawayo City Council (BCC) is currently under pressure to find a lasting solution to the problem after at least 13 people allegedly lost their lives after drinking contaminated water. Coca-Cola country manager, Milidzani Ncube, said the company has come onboard to mitigate the challenge by partnering DanChurchAid Zimbabwe in the project. “The funding will be used to conduct site surveys, drill six boreholes and equip the solar-driven water kiosks that will provide water to 2 181 families in Bulawayo. “The Coca-Cola Foundation and bottling partners Schweppes and Delta are proud to be responding to this water crisis that will enable more than 25 000 people to access much-needed safe and clean water daily.          googletag.cmd.push(function() { googletag.display('div-gpt-ad-1588599181508-1'); });      “Lack of access to safe water and sanitation services has direct health implications globally; many children die from diarrhoea every year and most of these deaths can be prevented through access to safe drinking water, adequate sanitation and good hygiene. “Water-related diseases contribute to undernutrition because they affect a person’s ability to absorb key nutrients and more than 50 percent of hospital visits are for preventable illnesses related to inadequate water and sanitation,” Ncube said. The borehole project which is part of Coca-Cola’s humanitarian support during the Covid-19 pandemic is set to be completed in six months’ time. Last year, Schweppes, a manufacturer and distributor of non-carbonated still beverages under licence from Coca-Cola in partnership with DanChurchAid provided 2 181 families with clean water in Bulawayo. In appreciation of the funding, DanChurchAid country director, Mads Schack Lindegard, lauded Coca-Cola Foundation for bringing the project to where it is needed the most. “With partners like the Coca-Cola Foundation, we are changing lives and supporting sustainable community initiatives,” Lindegard said. The water and sanitation project for the urban poor in Bulawayo is focused on addressing the problem of inadequate water and poor sanitation in low-income urban communities to contribute towards a lasting solution. Through partnerships with service providers including water utilities, local authorities like BCC and the communities these efforts will strengthen the capacity of service providers to deliver sustainable city-wide water and sanitation services, promote good hygiene and raise the standards of living. Sponsored Links                                              Classifieds.co.zw                                                                                                                      Property, Houses                                                                                                                                                      Building Supplies                                                                                                                                                      Electronics                                                                                                                                                      Cars                                                                                                             